  "prompt": "How do I reverse the words in a String without reversing each character and not using builtin functions like split and substring in C#?",
  "response": "To reverse the words in a string in C# without using built-in functions like `Split` or `Substring`, you can manually iterate through the string to identify spaces and reverse the order of the words.\n\nHere's a simple implementation to achieve this:\n\n```csharp\nusing System;\n\nclass Program\n{\n    static void Main()\n    {\n        string input = \"Hello World from ChatGPT\";\n        string reversed = ReverseWords(input);\n        Console.WriteLine(reversed);\n    }\n\n    static string ReverseWords(string s)\n    {\n        // First, we can count the words and store their start and end indexes\n        int count = 0;\n        for (int i = 0; i < s.Length; i++)\n        {\n            if (i == 0 || (s[i - 1] == ' ' && s[i] != ' '))\n            {\n                count++; // Increment count when we find the start of a new word\n            }\n        }\n\n        // Create an array to hold the words\n        string[] words = new string[count];\n        int wordIndex = 0;\n        int start = 0;\n\n        // Loop through the string again to extract words\n        for (int i = 0; i < s.Length; i++)\n        {\n            // Check for the start of a word\n            if (i == 0 || (s[i - 1] == ' ' && s[i] != ' '))\n            {\n                start = i; // Start of a new word\n            }\n            // Check for end of a word\n            if (i == s.Length - 1 || (s[i] != ' ' && s[i + 1] == ' '))\n            {\n                int end = i; // End of the word\n                words[wordIndex++] = ExtractWord(s, start, end);\n            }\n        }\n\n        // Now we need to assemble the reversed words into a result string\n        char[] result = new char[s.Length];\n        int position = 0;\n\n        // Add the words in reverse order\n        for (int i = words.Length - 1; i >= 0; i--)\n        {\n            for (int j = 0; j < words[i].Length; j++)\n            {\n                result[position++] = words[i][j];\n            }\n            if (i > 0) // Add a space after each word except the last one\n            {\n                result[position++] = ' ';\n            }\n        }\n\n        return new string(result, 0, position); // Return the new string constructed from the character array\n    }\n\n    static string ExtractWord(string s, int start, int end)\n    {\n        // Create a character array to store the word\n        char[] word = new char[end - start + 1];\n        int index = 0;\n\n        // Copy the characters from the string to the character array\n        for (int i = start; i <= end; i++)\n        {\n            word[index++] = s[i];\n        }\n\n        return new string(word); // Return the new string constructed from the character array\n    }\n}\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n1. **Counting Words**: First, the code counts the number of words based on spaces.\n2. **Extracting Words**: It then iterates through the string again to extract each word (from `start` to `end` indices) to an array called `words`.\n3. **Reversing Order**: Finally, the words are added to a result string in reverse order, ensuring to insert spaces appropriately except after the last word.\n4. **Helper Method**: A helper method `ExtractWord` is used to copy characters from the original string to create each word without using built-in functions.\n\nThis implementation does not use `Split`, `Substring`, or any other built-in string manipulation functions.",
